},"en":{"11 February 1174–9 February 1218":"11 February 1174–9 February 1218","1133–Female":"1133–Deceased","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1163–1220":"1163–1220","1220–1254":"1220–1254","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1191–1242":"1191–1242","1197–Male":"1197–Deceased","1230–1262":"1230–1262","–1223":"–1223","–1335":"–1335","after 1193":"after 1193","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","23 February 1224":"23 February 1224","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1163":"1163","1174":"1174","1250":"1250","9 February 1218":"9 February 1218","1191":"1191","1215":"1215","1335":"1335","1223":"1223","1254":"1254","1133":"1133","11 February 1174":"11 February 1174","about 1197":"about 1197","1218":"1218","Royton, Lancashire, England":"Royton, Lancashire, England","Spotbrough, Yorkshire, England":"Sprotbrough and Cusworth, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzWilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William FitzWilliam was born on 11 February 1174, in Sprotbrough and Cusworth, Yorkshire, England as the son of William FitzWilliam de Sprotborough and Avice de Tania. He married Adela de Warenne after 1193. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 9 February 1218, in Royton, Lancashire, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"11 February 1174–9 February 1218":"11. veebruar 1174–9. veebruar 1218","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1163–1220":"1163–1220","1220–1254":"1220–1254","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1191–1242":"1191–1242","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1230–1262":"1230–1262","–1223":"–1223","–1335":"–1335","after 1193":"pärast 1193","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","23 February 1224":"23. veebruar 1224","1230":"1230","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1163":"1163","1174":"1174","1250":"1250","9 February 1218":"9. veebruar 1218","1191":"1191","1215":"1215","1335":"1335","1223":"1